The High Commissioner of the United Nations Council for Human Rights issued a <a href="https://www.ohchr.org/EN/NewsEvents/Pages/DisplayNews.aspx?NewsID=23481&amp;LangID=E">statement</a> [press release, UNCHR] condemning Nicaragua's treatment of its citizens. High Commissioner, <span> Zeid Ra’ad Al Hussein,</span> called for Nicaragua to cease its acts of brutality against its people, and for the government to be held accountable for the nation's human rights violations.

<span>“I urge the Human Rights Council, and the broader international community, to take concrete action to prevent the current crisis from descending into deeper social and political turmoil. Any such action should aim to ensure full accountability for human rights violations and abuses, enable victims to have effective access to justice and appropriate remedies, including reparations and the right to know the truth,”, Zeid Ra’ad Al Hussein</span>

Nicaragua's began its <a href="https://www.jurist.org/news/2018/08/un-rights-experts-urge-nicaragua-to-stop-repressing-human-rights-defenders/">crackdown</a> [article, JURIST] against internal voices of dissent following a controversial attempt to reform the country's social security system back on April 18, 2018. The UN reported violations including <span>disproportionate use of force by police, extrajudicial killings; disappearances; arbitrary detentions without due process; torture; and restrictions on freedom of assembly and expression of opinions.</span>

Teachers, civil servants, and public doctors were dismissed. Also, <span>members of the Sandinista party, Government officials and members of the National Police were attacked, with 22 police officers killed. </span> By UN estimates, the crackdown has claimed the lives of 300 people with 2,000 injured.

